Q1: The Gaussian VaR at \(\alpha\) quantile of an investment \(I\) is \(VaR_{\alpha}=(\sigma Z_{\alpha}+\mu)I\). Suppose we have two investment, A and B. The returns of A is \(r_A \sim N(\mu_A,\sigma^2_A)\) and the returns of B is \(r_B\sim N(\mu_B,\sigma^2_B)\). The correlation between \(r_A\) and \(r_B\) is \(\rho_{AB}\). We have a portfolio, constructed by investing $0.5 in A and $0.5 in B.

(Hint: If you would like to use LaTeX to type the formula, you may refer to HW Template or this website: https://www.overleaf.com/learn/latex/List_of_Greek_letters_and_math_symbols)

  1. What is the distribution of our portfolio return, denoted by \(r_p\)?
  2. What is \(VaR_{\alpha}^p\) of our portfolio?
  3. Prove the subadditivity property of VaR holds.

solution:

  1. \(r_P\sim N(\mu_{A+B},\sigma^2_{A+B})\), where \(\sigma^2_{A+B}=0.25\sigma^2_A+0.25\sigma^2_B+2*0.25\rho_{AB}\sigma_A\sigma_B\).

  2. \(VaR^{A+B}_{\alpha}=-(\sigma_{A+B}*Z_{\alpha}+\mu_{A+B})*I\), where \(\sigma_{A+B}=(0.25\sigma^2_A+0.25\sigma^2_B+2*0.25\rho_{AB}\sigma_A\sigma_B)^{1/2}\).

  3. \(VaR_{\alpha}^{A}+VaR_{\alpha}^{B}= -(\sigma_A Z_{\alpha}+\mu_A)*I-(\sigma_B Z_{\alpha}+\mu_B)*I=-[Z_{\alpha}*(\sigma_A+\sigma_B)+\mu_{AB}]*I\).

As \(\rho_{AB}\leq1\), \(VaR^{A+B}_{\alpha}\leq VaR_{\alpha}^{A}+VaR_{\alpha}^{B}\).

Gaussian VaR:

Step3: Calculate Mean and Standard Deviation of Historical daily rets

# Calculate mean and sd for CSI300
mu_c = mean(CSI300$ret,na.rm=T)
sigma_c = sd(CSI300$ret,na.rm = T)
print(paste0("mu_c = ", mu_c))
## [1] "mu_c = 0.000343733247882493"

## [1] "sigma_c = 0.0157229199488836"
# Calculate mean and sd for FTSE350

## [1] "mu_f = 5.17332569948425e-05"

## [1] "sigma_f = 0.00860500973651667"

Step4: Calculate 5% VaR \(VaR^{A}_{\alpha}=-(\sigma_{A}*Z_{\alpha}+\mu_{A})*I\)

investment=1e6
q5 = qnorm(0.05)
var_C.q5 = -(sigma_c * q5 + mu_c) * investment
var_F.q5 = -(sigma_f * q5 + mu_f) * investment
print(paste0("CSI300 VaR(0.05) = ", round(var_C.q5,2)))
## [1] "CSI300 VaR(0.05) = 25518.17"
print(paste0("FTSE350 VaR(0.05) = ", round(var_F.q5,2)))
## [1] "FTSE350 VaR(0.05) = 14102.25"

Gaussian ES

es_C.q5 = investment * (mu_c+sigma_c*dnorm(qnorm(0.05))/0.05)
es_F.q5 = investment * (mu_f+sigma_f*dnorm(qnorm(0.05))/0.05)
print(paste0("ES_C.q5=",round(es_C.q5,2)))

Historical ES

CSI300$pl = CSI300$ret * investment
FTSE350$pl = FTSE350$ret * investment
# generate an empty dummy variable firstly
CSI300$dummy.q5=NA
CSI300[which(CSI300$pl<=(-var.hist_C.q5)),]$dummy.q5=1
FTSE350 = FTSE350 %>% mutate(dummy.q5=ifelse(pl<=(-var.hist_F.q5),1,NA))
#  Compute Average of Losses in Excess of VaR
CSI300$es.q5 = -CSI300$dummy.q5 * CSI300$pl
FTSE350$es.q5 = -FTSE350$dummy.q5 * FTSE350$pl
es.hist_C.q5 = mean(CSI300$es.q5,na.rm=T)
es.hist_F.q5 = mean(FTSE350$es.q5,na.rm=T)

cat("CSI300 Historical ES 0.05 = ",round(es.hist_C.q5,2),"\n")
## CSI300 Historical ES 0.05 =  41230.71
cat("FTSE350 Historical ES 0.05 = ",round(es.hist_F.q5,2),"\n")
## FTSE350 Historical ES 0.05 =  20577.26
  1. If you invest the two indices with equal weights in the first day and do not reallocate later on, and the total investment is still 1 million dollar. Calculate the historical and Gaussian \(VaR_{0.05}\) and the corresponding expeted shortfall for the portfolio. Compare the results with part a. What is your conclusion?

Step1: Calculate portfolio rets

port=ind.g.price %>% group_by(gvkeyx) %>% arrange(date) %>% mutate(ret=price/lag(price,1)-1) %>% ungroup
port= port %>% filter(!is.na(ret)) %>% group_by(gvkeyx) %>% 
        arrange(date) %>% mutate(cumret=cumprod(ret+1))%>% ungroup
port=port %>% group_by(date) %>% summarise(idx.p=mean(cumret)) %>% ungroup
port= port %>% arrange(date) %>% mutate(ret=idx.p/lag(idx.p,1)-1) %>% filter(!is.na(ret))

Step2: Calculate portfolio Gaussian VaR and Historical VaR

# Gaussian VaR
mu_p=mean(port$ret)
sigma_p=sd(port$ret)
print(paste0("mu_p = ", mu_p))
## [1] "mu_p = 0.000186424676403098"
print(paste0("sigma_p = ", sigma_p))
## [1] "sigma_p = 0.0107976114727058"
var_P.q5=-(sigma_p * q5 + mu_p) * investment
print(paste0(" portfolio VaR(0.05) = ", round(var_P.q5,2)))
## [1] " portfolio VaR(0.05) = 17574.07"
# Historical VaR
var.hist_P.q5 = -investment * quantile(port$ret, probs=0.05, type=3, na.rm=T)
print(paste0("portfolio VaR(0.05) = ", round(var.hist_P.q5,2)))
## [1] "portfolio VaR(0.05) = 16022.18"
# Gaussian ES
es_P_q5 = investment * (mu_p + sigma_p*dnorm(qnorm(0.05))/0.05)
print(paste0("Gaussian ES(0.05)=",round(es_P_q5,2)))
## [1] "Gaussian ES(0.05)=22458.8"
# Historical ES
port$pl = port$ret * investment
# generate an empty dummy variable firstly
port$dummy.q5=NA
port[which(port$pl<=(-var.hist_P.q5)),]$dummy.q5=1
#  Compute Average of Losses in Excess of VaR
port$es.q5 = -port$dummy.q5 * port$pl
es.hist_P.q5 = mean(port$es.q5,na.rm=T)

cat("portfolio Historical ES 0.05 = ",round(es.hist_P.q5,2))
## portfolio Historical ES 0.05 =  28473.19

Q3: Use the data obtained from Q2. Calculate the probability that returns of the two indices are both negative in one day, and then calculate the co-drawdown.

df3 = merge(CSI300, FTSE350, all.x = T, all.y = T) %>% 
        select(date, gvkeyx, dd)
codd = spread(df3, gvkeyx, dd)
colnames(codd)=c('date','dd_F','dd_C')
summary(codd)
##       date                 dd_F               dd_C        
##  Min.   :2014-01-03   Min.   :-0.18820   Min.   :-0.4670  
##  1st Qu.:2015-04-07   1st Qu.:-0.07640   1st Qu.:-0.3763  
##  Median :2016-07-01   Median :-0.03080   Median :-0.2980  
##  Mean   :2016-06-30   Mean   :-0.04758   Mean   :-0.2493  
##  3rd Qu.:2017-09-22   3rd Qu.:-0.01360   3rd Qu.:-0.0679  
##  Max.   :2018-12-28   Max.   : 0.00000   Max.   : 0.0000
codd = codd %>% 
  mutate(anydown = pmin(dd_C,dd_F)) %>% 
  mutate(codown = pmax(dd_C,dd_F))
codd = codd %>% mutate(neg.signal=ifelse(codown<0,1,NA))
prob.neg = sum(codd$neg.signal, na.rm=T)/length(codd$date)
cat('the probability that rets of the two indices are both negative is ',prob.neg)
## the probability that rets of the two indices are both negative is  0.8962025
# make plot
codd$zeroline=0
yrange=range(df3$dd)
plot(codd$dd_C~codd$date,
     type='l', lwd = 2, col = 'blue',
     xlab = 'date',ylab ='dd',ylim=yrange,
     main='Co-drawdown')

lines(codd$dd_F~codd$date,
